Scottish independent schools have achieved a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities only underline this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils throughout Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and strive to provide the best possible level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individualized school curriculums, we observe that modern languages are still popular and in demand in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, it goes straight into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is an important observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s tests show that languages are at the top of the tables, with the highest success rates being achieved by independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of Mandarin students, 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students achieved the highest A mark.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland promote foreign languages as important skills that children and youth will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by pupils are equally valued in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that for reasons that employers cite as problems in filling vacancies, 17% are under-skilled.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalized world.
Whatever career you choose, if you learn a second language, you will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, namely 15 percent, being frank.
That is why it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially those of developing economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the language it teaches.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in view of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have at independent schools a choice of several languages with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what awaits them in the future.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are vitally important for the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and attraction.
You have to do it right.
