The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and a women's hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to begin the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you only telling me this now, in my last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce a course after finding that students were really sleepy during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of student colleges where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another part, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of lack of sleep is also growing.
Enough good quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid catching up, because sleep deprivation switches the brain into starvation mode, so a person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that took one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
It hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
