Red Tide Update: Concentrations Decrease in Pinellas, Manatee, and Sarasota Districts
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to an overall drop in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC report, stains of flowering water are now reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this suggests decreasing concentration.
The blossoming water of the red tide has a range of about 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinellas district to the southern Lee district.
Spots were observed about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsborough County, but last week it was already relatively fewer places.
The red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported at the coast or in the open sea at the Pinellas district. In the Hillsborough district, low to high concentrations were observed at the open sea, the lowest to high concentrations in the Manatee district, the lowest to high concentrations at the coast or at the highest concentration at the open sea at the Saratoga district.
Respiratory irritation continues to occur in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
Respiratory irritation was not reported in northwestern Florida last week.
